  "text": "Chantraine et al. [CITATION_1] studied a large sample of patients with GHS for less than 1 month in which onehalf received conventional therapy (orthotic) and the other half received conventional therapy plus FES. Follow-up examinations conducted at 6 months, 1 year, and 2 years after therapy showed that, compared with the group that received conventional therapy, in the group treated with conventional therapy plus FES, the management of pain was better, the number of patients with radiological evidence of subluxation had decreased significantly, and motor recovery had significantly improved. The best performances of the FEStreated group were also maintained at a follow-up after 24 months.",
